spanGrp.span: ‘A man and a woman live far away in the bush, where there are many wild cats.
Pekaga jamẽ pemina sẽr-gẽ komĩ' (eh) kã'yiga mãĩ tã'ĩ jirö karbö tsõ ska
They have a young boy; he walks already.
Pekaga jamẽ pemina rö yaba ta dlunã kipashke-ka Yaba shkö-gẽ-ka
The lady pampers the child and puts him to sleep.
pemina të yaba jẽrshewẽ-gẽ Jeska í kemẽ-gẽ-ite köpö ska
The father is in another place, and the two of them go to the river to wash their clothes.
í kaga dul kwãwã í í mĩ-gẽu-lo (m) ñapawö diglö köga
They leave the child asleep in bed.
Í yaba jeche-gẽ-ite köpö jaka inga
At that point they went to wash their clothes and two small deer came by where the child was sleeping.
Je_jueta jie-wa mẽnẽu-lo (m) ñapawö jueta mululbe yabla deu-lo yaba mãĩ yaba kã'lmẽ köpö ska
Yaba wöbötsá-wã je mululbe yabla wa
the deer ran into the bush, he chased them into the bush to play with them.
Yaba të je mululbe yaba töjiá-tula-mĩ kã'yaga jãrga Je töjiáu-mĩ-ite jeska í mẽnẽu-mĩ kã'yaga nã mululbe yabla ra jinõ
There a big snake appeared before the child;
Jeska kebé tã'ĩ desãu yaba wömĩ
it rolled up the child and lifted him all the way up to a branch.
(_) yaba yaba butrá-wã yaba të/ yaba mẽnẽu-mĩ kebé kebé të yaba bötsá-ka komĩ' kaljula jãrga ska
The child pulled out the snake’s tongue, so the snake got scared and let the child go.
Yaba të kebé köktö yá köktö ĩa yá ĩa Je kueinga kebé kebé mẽletenã'-wã-te yaba yáu-mĩ-nẽ
The child fell down and found another big creature;
Yaba janã'wã Jeska yaba ñã kwá-wã-nẽ e-gla bichi tã'ĩ
jera yaba ñã kwá-wã-nẽ je jinã' yaba ra
and then the child remained alone;
the small deer came around and played.
His parents came back home and thought the child was dead, as the child was lost;
pekaga jamẽ pemina de-mĩu-lo-nẽ jũ ska nẽra (m) begetsá-ite yaba döá-wã yaba shenã'-wã í (_)
they began to search for the (dead?) child
but they could not find him; so they broke in tears.
Jeranã (_) ka ĩã kõr ka ĩã kõr Ñerö í ñã gagá jiñã' kulomĩ (_)
[They wondered whether] the child was lost or dead.
Mãga í yaba shenã'-wã yaba döá-wã le í
There came the wild dogs and the father wanted to kill them because he thought they were the ones that had killed the child.
Jeskara chichi kalbö deu-lo je biá (m) ktewã í kaga të Begetsá-nã je të í yaba katá-wã rö nẽ
But they did not know that they child was playing far in the bush; he was playing with wild animals, like snakes and deer.
Pero ka inga í juenẽ-ra-nã í yaba tsõ rö komĩ' kã'yaga nã jinõ kal/ (_) jirö jirö tsõ kalbö jãrga kebé bi mululbe yabla bi je ra í tsõ jinõ (_) kã'yaga jãrga komĩ'
His parents went on crying and searching for him in vain.
Jeska pekaga-wa jiñõ-gẽ tã'ĩ të yaba yule-gẽ köũ ka í kõr ĩã
Thus the child remained in the bush and lived there.’
jebi yaba mĩ-gẽu jatanã-gẽ-wã kã'yaga nã senã'
